program        → declaration* EOF;

declaration    → funDecl | varDecl;

funDecl        → TYPE function ;
varDecl        → TYPE IDENTIFIER ( "=" expression )? ";" ;

block          → "{" ( declaration | statement )* "}" ;

statement      → exprStmt
               | block ;

exprStmt       → expression ";" ;


function       → IDENTIFIER "(" parameters? ")" block ;
parameters     → TYPE IDENTIFIER ( "," TYPE IDENTIFIER )* ;

TYPE           → "i16" | "i32" | "u16" | "u32" ;
NUMBER         → DIGIT+ ( "." DIGIT+ )? ;
STRING         → "\"" <any char except "\"">* "\"" ;
IDENTIFIER     → ALPHA ( ALPHA | DIGIT )* ;
ALPHA          → "a" ... "z" | "A" ... "Z" | "_" ;
DIGIT          → "0" ... "9" ;

All global function and variable declarations come into existence at the start of the source file, no matter where they are actually listed in the source file.
An exception to this are other global variables, which may only reference variables declared before them in the source file.
Global variables may not call functions in their initializers. When that is needed, the function call must be executed from within the main (or any other) function.

Local variables come into existence at the point where they are declared.

Variables may shadow other variables from enclosing scopes.
If a Variable shadows another variable from an enclosing scope, it may not use that variable's value in its own declaration.

Functions may only be declared in the global scope.

A function's parameters are treated to be in the same scope as the function's code.